OpenAI is pushing deeper into enterprise adoption, now courting private equ=
ity firms.

On Monday, a [Reuters report](https://www.reuters.com/business/openai-court=
s-private-equity-join-enterprise-ai-venture-sources-say-2026-03-16/) reveal=
ed that OpenAI is in talks with private equity firms TPG, Bain, Brookfield,=
 and Advent to form a joint venture with a pre-money valuation of $10 billi=
on, citing people close to the matter.=C2=A0

Shortly after the news broke, Fidji Simo, CEO of Applications at OpenAI, co=
nfirmed the news, saying OpenAI is =E2=80=9Cexcited to be building a deploy=
ment arm and will share more details soon.=E2=80=9D The benefits for OpenAI=
 include capturing more enterprise clients, typically a sector in which Ope=
nAI has lagged behind competitors.

In an [interview with The Wall Street Journal](https://www.wsj.com/tech/ai/=
openai-chatgpt-side-projects-16b3a825), Simo said that OpenAI was reducing =
its "side quests" and experimental projects and dedicating more resources t=
o coding and working with enterprise businesses.

In her [X post](https://x.com/fidjissimo/status/2033537381907710092?s=3D20)=
, Simo said the new deployment arm has been in the works since December and=
 focuses on embedding engineers directly within enterprise clients to enabl=
e closer collaboration. The Reuters report provided more information on how=
 the deal would operate, including:=20


* The private equity investors commit $4 billion in return for equity stake=
s, a say in how OpenAI=E2=80=99s solutions are deployed across its portfoli=
o companies, board seats and early access to OpenAI=E2=80=99s enterprise to=
ols.=C2=A0

* TPG would commit the most capital, serving as the anchor investor, while =
Advent, Bain, and Brookfield would be co-founding investors.=C2=A0

* The firms would get an equity stake of approximately $1 billion, though t=
he source told Reuters the numbers and plan details were subject to change.=
=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CThis is essentially part of running a sales motion. It will help t=
hem [OpenAI] sell more of their services/tokens,=E2=80=9D said Eric Compton=
, director of equity research, technology at Morningstar.=C2=A0

Beyond the benefits listed in the deals, private equity firms also have str=
ategic reasons to participate.=C2=A0

=E2=80=9CThey are 100% motivated to 'not fall behind' and risk not having s=
uccessful exits for their assets, so having a direct seat at the table in t=
his process will help further that goal in their eyes,=E2=80=9D added Compt=
on.=C2=A0

Simo highlighted the urgency and demand for AI solutions among enterprises,=
 noting that nearly 1 million businesses are running on OpenAI products, wi=
th API usage jumping 20% in the week after GPT-5.4 launched. Furthermore, s=
he said, Frontier, the platform OpenAI launched last month to help enterpri=
ses manage AI coworkers, is having more demand than the company can handle.

